    slug: "isaayiat-tajziyah-aur-mutaliyah",
    description: `Isaayiat - Tajziyah aur Mutaliyah is an Urdu-language scholarly work that provides a detailed analytical study (tajziyah) and critical examination (mutaliyah) of the Book of Isaiah (Isaayiat), which is one of the major prophetic books of the Old Testament in the Christian Bible. The book approaches this Biblical text from an Islamic academic perspective, examining its content, structure, historical context, and theological claims in light of Islamic scholarship, Quranic teachings, and the established principles of textual analysis. This work fills an important niche in Urdu Islamic literature, as there are relatively few comprehensive Urdu-language studies that subject Biblical texts to the same rigorous academic scrutiny that Islamic scholars have traditionally applied to their own primary texts.

The book begins with an introduction to the Book of Isaiah, providing essential background information including the traditional attribution of the book to the Prophet Isaiah (who is recognized in Islam as one of the prophets of Allah, known as Isaiah ibn Amoz), the historical period in which the book was composed, the political and social conditions of the Kingdom of Judah during Isaiah's ministry, and the literary structure and organization of the sixty-six chapters that make up the book in its current form. The author discusses the scholarly consensus regarding the multiple authorship of Isaiah, noting that critical Biblical scholarship divides the book into three sections: First Isaiah (chapters 1-39), Second Isaiah or Deutero-Isaiah (chapters 40-55), and Third Isaiah or Trito-Isaiah (chapters 56-66), each attributed to different authors writing in different historical periods.

The analytical sections of the book examine the major themes and passages of Isaiah in detail, including the prophecies concerning the coming of a messianic figure, the descriptions of God's judgment and mercy, the oracles against various nations, and the vision of a future ideal age. The author evaluates these passages from an Islamic perspective, comparing the concepts found in Isaiah with corresponding teachings in the Quran and the authentic hadith, and identifying areas of agreement, partial overlap, and fundamental divergence between the Biblical and Quranic worldviews. The book pays particular attention to those passages in Isaiah that are frequently cited in Christian theology as prophecies about Jesus Christ, examining these claims critically in light of the original Hebrew text, the historical context, and the Islamic understanding of prophethood and revelation. The Urdu prose is scholarly and methodical, with references to the original Hebrew and English translations of Isaiah, as well as to the relevant Quranic verses and classical Islamic commentaries. This book is intended for advanced students of comparative religion, Islamic scholars, Christian-Muslim dialogue participants, and educated Urdu readers who are interested in understanding the relationship between Biblical and Quranic teachings through a rigorous academic lens.`,
    metaDescription: "Isaayiat Tajziyah aur Mutaliyah is an Urdu analytical study of the Book of Isaiah from an Islamic perspective. Comparative religion with scholarly rigor."
