    slug: "islam-a-total-beginners-guide-3",
    description: `Islam a Total Beginners Guide (3) is the third and final volume in the comprehensive English-language introductory series on Islam, designed for readers who have completed the first two volumes and are ready to explore more advanced and nuanced aspects of the Islamic faith. While the first volume covered the fundamentals of Islamic creed and the five pillars, and the second volume expanded into Islamic history, social teachings, and ethical principles, this third volume addresses the more sophisticated dimensions of Islamic knowledge that are essential for a well-rounded understanding of the religion. The book is written in the same clear and accessible English style as the earlier volumes, but the content assumes that the reader has already acquired a basic familiarity with Islamic beliefs and practices.

The book begins with an introduction to Islamic law and jurisprudence (shariah and fiqh) at an introductory level, explaining the sources of Islamic law (the Quran, the Sunnah, consensus or ijma, and analogical reasoning or qiyas), the major schools of Islamic jurisprudence (Hanafi, Maliki, Shafi'i, and Hanbali), and how Islamic legal rulings are derived and applied. This section is designed to give beginners a basic understanding of how Islamic law works without delving into the technical details that would be covered in advanced fiqh textbooks. The book explains the different categories of rulings (obligatory, recommended, permissible, disliked, and prohibited) and provides examples of how these categories apply to various aspects of daily life.

The volume also covers the Islamic spiritual tradition, including the science of purifying the heart and soul (tazkiyat al-nafs), the concept of ihsan (excellence in worship and character), and an introduction to the Islamic tradition of Sufism (tasawwuf) presented in its authentic scholarly context. The book addresses common contemporary questions and challenges facing Muslims in the modern world, including the relationship between Islam and science, Islam and human rights, the role of women in Islam, Islamic finance, and how Muslims can maintain their faith and practice in non-Muslim societies. A section on comparative religion from an Islamic perspective provides a respectful but clear explanation of how Islam differs from other major world religions and what Islam teaches about interfaith relations. The final chapters provide guidance for continued learning, recommending specific books, resources, and study paths for readers who wish to deepen their knowledge beyond this introductory series. The English prose is engaging and intellectually stimulating, making this final volume a fitting capstone to what is one of the most comprehensive introductory series on Islam available in the English language.`,
